arch:property.oc:show_val: This is a lamb burial in a human burial in space 112. Most of the front legs were given a cluster unit number 10828. Since it is emphatically all one animal and all one event, that material is included here under this number. The lamb is a complete skeleton sharing a cut with an adult male human. A clearly defined brownish layer of phytoliths (?) covered the human skeleton and dipped down under the lamb, establishing their contemporaneity. The lamb was placed very carefully in an unnatural position, apparently so as to lie next to but not over the human body. It was laid on its left side, and the hind legs were held up at an angle while dirt was dumped in on top of the phytolithy layer. This left the hind legs extended out straight back and on a slope at roughly a 45 degree angle. As the body decayed, small bones such as sesamoids and the patellae rolled down the slope and ended up near the knees or pelvis (both patellae were by the pelvis). Meanwhile, the two front legs were held with the feet together going straight up (almost at right angles to the body on its left side, so the forequarters were twisted) while the pit was filled. Again, as the body decayed the sesamoids rolled down to the shoulders, and on both fore and hind feet some of the phalanges collapsed downward. Otherwise, everything was in anatomical position, and clearly the animal went into the grave intact. The earliest fusing articulations have just fused, with traces of epiphyseal lines (distal humerus, second phalanx). The pelvis, though, does not have an epiphyseal line. The teeth indicate a late infantile age, with the first molars just coming into wear.
